{"title_page": "John D. Terry", "text_new": "</ref>[[File:John Darling Terry.jpg|thumb|John Darling Terry]]\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name          = John D. Terry (Medal of Honor)\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1845|09|03}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1919|03|04|1845|09|03}}\n|birth_place   = [[Montville, Maine]]\n|death_place   = [[Manhattan]], New York\n|placeofburial = Bronx, New York\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = 1861\u20131863, 1863-1865\n|rank          = [[Sergeant#United States|Sergeant]], [[Lieutenant#United States|Lieutenant]], [[Captain#United States|Captain]], [[Major#United States|Major (brevet)]]\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|Massachusetts}} Company E, 23rd Massachusetts Infantry, 35th U.S. Colored Troops Infantry\n|battles       = [[Battle of New Bern]]<br/>[[American Civil War]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n|spouse        = Emma Celia Brown (m. 1866)\n|children.     = 10, 9 surviving to adulthood}}\n\n'''John Darling Terry''' (September 3, 1845 \u2013 March 4, 1919) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Terry received the [[Medal of Honor]] for bravery during combat.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=1870|title=Valor awards for John Darling Terry|website=valor.militarytimes.com|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> Terry's medal was won for \"extraordinary heroism\" during the [[Battle of New Bern]] in [[North Carolina]] on March 14, 1862.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was honored with the award on October 12, 1867.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_sz.html#TERRY|title=Medal of Honor Recipients - Civil War (S-Z)|website=U.S. Army Center of Military History|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nTerry was born in [[Montville, Maine]]. He joined the Army from [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]] in September 1861, and was discharged due to the loss of his leg in March 1863.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/massachusettssol21931mass#page/n755/mode/2up|title=Massachusetts soldiers, sailors, and marines in the civil war|website=archive.org|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> While recovering in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City|New York]] he volunteered for service during the draft riots.  He commanded a body of convalescent soldiers in July 1863 and on day three of the riots he received word that he was re-entering service as a lieutenant in the 1st North Carolina Colored Volunteers (later known as the 35th U.S. Colored Troops), a regiment he fought with until the war's end.  On May 23, 1865, after the official end of the war, Terry was promoted to Captain.  However, in the aftermath of the war's end and due to prejudice against officers working with the former slaves, his promotion was withdrawn.  In September of 1865 Terry was assigned to the Freedman's Bureau and while there was brevetted promotions to Captain and Major before his discharge.  He died in [[Manhattan]] on March 4, 1919,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42016372/major_j_d_terry/ |title=Major J. D. Terry |work=[[New-York Tribune]] |page=11 |date=1919-03-06 |access-date=2020-01-10 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|website=Ancestry.com|title=New York, New York, Extracted Death Index, 1862-1948|url=https://www.ancestry.com/search/collections/9131/|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref> and was buried at [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)]], Butternut Plot, Section 141, Lot 14454.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHis official rank remained Lieutenant until 2013, almost 150 years later, when his great grandson and other family members petitioned the ABCMR to reinstate his official rank of Captain. After careful review the board determined that the evidence presented was sufficient and corrected the record reinstating Terry's permanent rank to Captain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/article/100410/|title=army_honors_highly_decorated_civil_war_soldier|website=army.mil|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|The President of the United States of America, in the name of Congress, takes pleasure in presenting the Medal of Honor to Sergeant John Darling Terry, United States Army, for extraordinary heroism on 14 March 1862, while serving with Company E, 23d Massachusetts Infantry, in action at New Bern, North Carolina. In the thickest of the fight, where he lost his leg by a shot, Sergeant Terry still encouraged the men until carried off the field.<ref name=\":0\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: T\u2013Z]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terry, John D.}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:American amputees]]\n[[Category:People of Maine in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Montville, Maine]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n", "text_old": "</ref>[[File:John Darling Terry.jpg|thumb|John Darling Terry]]\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name          = John D. Terry (Medal of Honor)\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1845|09|03}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1919|03|04|1845|09|03}}\n|birth_place   = [[Montville, Maine]]\n|death_place   = [[Manhattan]], New York\n|placeofburial = Bronx, New York\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = 1861\u20131863, 1863-1865\n|rank          = [[Sergeant#United States|Sergeant]], [[Lieutenant#United States|Lieutenant]], [[Captain#United States|Captain]], [[Major#United States|Major (brevet)]]\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|Massachusetts}} Company E, 23rd Massachusetts Infantry, 35th U.S. Colored Troops Infantry\n|battles       = [[Battle of New Bern]]<br/>[[American Civil War]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n|spouse        = Emma Celia Brown (m. 1866)\n|children.     = 10, 9 surviving to adulthood}}\n\n'''John Darling Terry''' (September 3, 1845 \u2013 March 4, 1919) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Terry received the [[Medal of Honor]] for bravery during combat.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=1870|title=Valor awards for John Darling Terry|website=valor.militarytimes.com|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> Terry's medal was won for \"extraordinary heroism\" during the [[Battle of New Bern]] in [[North Carolina]] on March 14, 1862.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was honored with the award on October 12, 1867.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_sz.html#TERRY|title=Medal of Honor Recipients - Civil War (S-Z)|website=U.S. Army Center of Military History|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nTerry was born in [[Montville, Maine]]. He joined the Army from [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]] in September 1861, and was discharged due to the loss of his leg in March 1863.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/massachusettssol21931mass#page/n755/mode/2up|title=Massachusetts soldiers, sailors, and marines in the civil war|website=archive.org|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> While recovering in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City|New York]] he volunteered for service during the draft riots.  He commanded a body of convalescent soldiers in July 1863 and on day three of the riots he received word that he was re-entering service as a lieutenant in the 1st North Carolina Colored Volunteers (later known as the 35th U.S. Colored Troops), a regiment he fought with until the war's end.  On May 23, 1865, after the official end of the war, Terry was promoted to Captain.  However, in the aftermath of the war's end and due to prejudice against officers working with the former slaves, his promotion was withdrawn.  In September of 1865 Terry was assigned to the Freedman's Bureau and while there was brevetted promotions to Captain and Major before his discharge.  He died in [[Manhattan]] on March 4, 1919,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42016372/major_j_d_terry/ |title=Major J. D. Terry |work=[[New-York Tribune]] |page=11 |date=1919-03-06 |access-date=2020-01-10 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|website=Ancestry.com|title=New York, New York, Extracted Death Index, 1862-1948|url=https://www.ancestry.com/search/collections/9131/[database on-line]|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref> and was buried at [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)]], Butternut Plot, Section 141, Lot 14454.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHis official rank remained Lieutenant until 2013, almost 150 years later, when his great grandson and other family members petitioned the ABCMR to reinstate his official rank of Captain. After careful review the board determined that the evidence presented was sufficient and corrected the record reinstating Terry's permanent rank to Captain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/article/100410/|title=army_honors_highly_decorated_civil_war_soldier|website=army.mil|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|The President of the United States of America, in the name of Congress, takes pleasure in presenting the Medal of Honor to Sergeant John Darling Terry, United States Army, for extraordinary heroism on 14 March 1862, while serving with Company E, 23d Massachusetts Infantry, in action at New Bern, North Carolina. In the thickest of the fight, where he lost his leg by a shot, Sergeant Terry still encouraged the men until carried off the field.<ref name=\":0\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: T\u2013Z]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terry, John D.}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:American amputees]]\n[[Category:People of Maine in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Montville, Maine]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n", "name_user": "Dtmacl", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_D._Terry"}
